transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Hello, thank you for participating in this interview. I'm going to ask you some questions about your health and experiences. Let's begin.

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Hello! Thank you for having me. I'm ready to answer your questions. 

1. To start, can you tell me a little about your experiences with healthcare so far? Have you had any challenges accessing care?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me a bit about yourself and your current life situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Sure! I'm currently a college student living in a suburban area of Los Angeles. I come from a low-income family, so finances can be pretty tight, which adds a lot of stress to my life. I don't have health insurance right now, so I rely on free community healthcare clinics for my medical needs. 

I've had to navigate some challenges when it comes to accessing care, especially when I need to see a doctor or get medications. Sometimes, I have to wait a long time for appointments, and it can be hard to get the help I need, especially with my busy school schedule. Overall, it's been a bit of a struggle, but I'm doing my best to manage it. 

Interviewer: Thank you for sharing that, Samantha. It sounds like you've been facing quite a few challenges. Can you tell me more about your experiences with any specific healthcare services you've used, particularly in relation to prenatal care or reproductive health?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your pregnancy or pregnancies? When did you first learn you were pregnant?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I actually found out I was pregnant a little over a year ago. It was really unexpected, and I was pretty overwhelmed at first. I remember taking a home pregnancy test after missing my period, and when it came back positive, I just felt a rush of emotions—fear, anxiety, and a bit of excitement too. 

At that time, I wasn't in a stable situation, financially or emotionally, so I knew I had to figure out what to do next. I went to the community clinic for my first appointment because I didn’t have insurance. They were really helpful and provided me with the information I needed, but I still felt lost and stressed about everything.

I ended up deciding not to continue with the pregnancy, which was a really tough choice for me. The clinic staff was supportive during that time, but it was still a lot to handle, especially with everything else going on in my life. 

Since then, I've been trying to focus on my health and make sure I'm taking care of myself, but I still struggle with the financial stress and trying to balance school. It’s a lot. 

Interviewer: That sounds like a very challenging experience, Samantha. Thank you for being so open about it. Can you tell me more about how you felt during that time regarding the support you received from the clinic? Did you feel like your needs were being met?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: When did you first seek prenatal care? What was that experience like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Persona: I first sought prenatal care right after I found out I was pregnant, which was around the time I went to the community clinic for my initial appointment. They were the only place I could go since I didn't have insurance, and I was really nervous about how things would go.

When I arrived at the clinic, I was greeted by some very compassionate staff members who took the time to listen to my story and my concerns. They provided me with information about my options, which was helpful. However, I did feel a bit overwhelmed by the medical terms and what I was supposed to do next. 

The clinic offered me an ultrasound and scheduled follow-up appointments, which made me feel like I was being taken care of. But I also felt a bit rushed at times because they were so busy. I remember waiting for hours for my appointment, which only added to my anxiety. 

Overall, I appreciated the support I received, but I wished I had more time to ask questions and process everything. It felt like there was a lot of information to absorb, and sometimes I just needed someone to sit down with me and explain things in a simpler way. 

Interviewer: It’s understandable to feel that way, especially in such a significant moment in your life. Did you have any specific concerns at that time about your health or the pregnancy that you wanted to discuss with the healthcare providers?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who is providing your prenatal care? Can you describe your relationship with your healthcare provider?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I was getting my prenatal care from the community clinic where I initially went for my pregnancy. The staff there was really friendly, and I had a nurse practitioner who I saw regularly. She was nice and tried to answer my questions, but sometimes I felt like I was just another patient on her list. 

I appreciated her support, but I didn’t feel like I had a strong connection with her. I think part of that was due to the busy environment of the clinic—there were so many people coming in and out, and I often felt rushed through my appointments. 

I did have a few moments where I felt comfortable enough to share my worries about my health and the pregnancy, especially when it came to my stress levels and how they might affect everything. But I wish I could have had more one-on-one time to really dive into my concerns and get more personalized advice. 

Since I wasn't sure what to expect, I sometimes left feeling like I still had questions that weren’t fully answered, especially when it came to my mental health and how to cope with the stress I was under. 

Interviewer: It sounds like you were navigating a lot during that time, and I can understand how wanting a deeper connection with your healthcare provider could help. Did you have any specific questions or topics that you felt were important to address but didn't get the chance to discuss?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How often do you have prenatal appointments? Can you walk me through what a typical visit is like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Persona: I was having prenatal appointments about once a month, especially in the early stages of my pregnancy. Each visit usually started with me checking in at the front desk, and then I'd wait in the waiting area for quite a while—sometimes over an hour. 

When I finally got called in, the nurse would take my vitals, like my blood pressure and weight, and then I’d wait for the nurse practitioner to come in. During the appointments, she would ask me how I was feeling and if I had any concerns. We’d also go over any lab results or tests I had done, like blood work or the ultrasound.

The visits would be pretty quick—maybe 15 to 20 minutes. We’d discuss my health and the baby’s development, but I often felt like we skimmed over a lot of important topics. For example, I wanted to know more about how my stress could impact the pregnancy or what resources were available for someone in my financial situation, but I didn’t always feel comfortable bringing those things up in the short time we had. 

Sometimes, it felt more like a checklist for her than an actual conversation. I would leave feeling relieved that everything was okay, but also a bit confused or anxious about the things I hadn’t said or asked. I really wanted to understand how to take care of myself better during that time, and I wish we had more time to talk about those issues. 

Interviewer: It seems like you had a lot on your mind during those visits, and I can see why you would want more time to discuss your concerns. Were there any particular resources or support systems you were hoping to access to help with your stress or overall health during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you experienced any health concerns or complications during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Persona: Thankfully, I didn’t experience any major complications during my pregnancy, but I did have some health concerns that made me anxious. For example, I was dealing with high stress levels, mostly due to my financial situation and family pressures, which I worried could affect my health and the pregnancy. 

I also had some issues with gingivitis that I was trying to manage at the same time, which added to my stress. The clinic staff did address it, but again, I felt rushed during those discussions. They prescribed some mouthwash and encouraged me to keep up with dental hygiene, but I sometimes found it hard to fully understand how to prevent it from getting worse. 

Additionally, I had a couple of bouts of viral sinusitis during that period. The clinic helped me with that too by giving me some recommendations for over-the-counter medications, but I was still concerned about how these issues might impact my overall well-being while pregnant. 

Overall, I was just trying to stay on top of everything and do my best to take care of myself, but it was definitely a challenge to balance all those health concerns alongside the pregnancy.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What medications or supplements are you currently taking?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I’m not currently taking any prescription medications, but I have been using an over-the-counter mouthwash for the gingivitis, as the clinic recommended. They suggested I use that to help manage the issue. I also occasionally take vitamin supplements, like prenatal vitamins, to support my overall health, especially since I was pregnant. 

However, I still sometimes forget to take them regularly, especially with my busy schedule and everything else going on in my life. I know it's important, but it can be hard to keep track. I wish I had more guidance on what supplements I should be prioritizing, especially since I’m trying to manage my health effectively. 

Interviewer: It sounds like you're doing your best to maintain your health, but I understand how challenging it can be to keep track of everything amidst your busy life. Have you ever discussed with your healthcare provider the importance of medication adherence or any specific supplements you might need?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your diet and nutrition during pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Persona: During my pregnancy, I tried to pay more attention to my diet and nutrition, but it was definitely a struggle. Since I come from a low-income family, sometimes healthy food options are harder to access, and I often have to rely on what’s affordable and available. 

I mostly tried to eat fruits and vegetables when I could, but I also found myself eating a lot of quick, convenient meals like ramen or frozen dinners because they were cheaper and easier to make with my busy schedule. I know those aren’t the healthiest options, but it can be tough to prioritize cooking when I have school and everything else going on.

I did make an effort to include things like whole grains and proteins in my meals, and I tried to drink a lot of water. I also made sure to take the prenatal vitamins to help with any gaps in my nutrition. But honestly, I often felt guilty about not being able to eat as healthily as I wanted to, especially knowing how important nutrition is during pregnancy.

I wish I had more guidance on what specific foods would be best for me and the baby, as well as resources to help me afford healthier options. It can be really overwhelming trying to figure it all out on my own. 

Interviewer: It sounds like you're aware of the importance of nutrition during pregnancy, but the challenges you're facing make it difficult to meet those goals. Have you had any conversations with your healthcare provider about nutrition, or have you received any specific advice or resources related to healthy eating during pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How have you been feeling emotionally during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Persona: Honestly, my emotional state during my pregnancy has been quite a rollercoaster. I started off feeling overwhelmed and anxious after finding out I was pregnant. There were so many emotions—fear about my financial situation and how I would manage everything, but also some excitement about the possibility of becoming a mom.

As time went on, the stress really took a toll on me. I often felt anxious, especially with the pressure of school, finances, and family issues. I worried about how my stress might affect the pregnancy and the baby, which only added to my feelings of guilt and anxiety. I sometimes felt isolated, too, as I didn't have a strong support system to talk to about what I was experiencing.

I did have moments of joy and connection, especially when I would think about the future and what it might hold. But there were also days when I felt really low and struggled to find motivation to do much of anything. I wished I had more resources for mental health support, especially during such a significant time in my life.

I did try to reach out to friends occasionally, but it was hard for them to understand what I was going through, and I didn’t want to burden them with my worries. I think if I had someone to talk to who understood the challenges of being a young, uninsured pregnant woman, it would have made a big difference for me. 

Interviewer: It’s completely understandable to feel that way, especially given everything you’re juggling. Have you had any opportunities to discuss your emotional well-being with your healthcare provider, or do you feel there’s a lack of support in that area?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who supports you during your pregnancy? Can you tell me about your support network?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Persona: My support network is pretty limited, unfortunately. I have a few friends who I've tried to talk to about what I'm going through, but they often have their own challenges, so it can be hard to lean on them for support. I don’t want to overwhelm them with my worries, so I often keep things to myself.

My family is also going through a tough time financially, which makes it hard for them to be supportive. They care about me, but they have their own stressors to deal with, and sometimes I feel like I don't want to add to their burdens. 

I think one of the hardest parts is feeling isolated. I wish I had someone who could really understand what it's like to be a young woman facing these challenges, especially with being uninsured and trying to figure out my health and pregnancy. 

Sometimes, I try to find support online through forums or social media groups, where I can connect with others who might be going through similar experiences. That helps a bit, but it’s not the same as having someone in-person who can offer real support. I often find myself wishing for more community resources or programs that could provide emotional support for young pregnant women like me. 

Interviewer: It’s clear that you’re navigating a lot on your own, and I can see how valuable a supportive network would be during this time. Have you considered or explored any community resources that might offer emotional support or guidance for pregnant women?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about your birth plan? What are your preferences for delivery?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Persona: Yes, I have thought about my birth plan a bit, even though it’s still a bit overwhelming to consider. Since I’m still in school and managing everything else, I haven’t put together a detailed plan, but I do have some preferences.

I would like to have a natural birth if possible, but I also want to be flexible depending on how things go. I’ve read some about the different options for pain management, and I think I’d like to try to manage without medication if I can, but I’m open to whatever helps me and the baby during delivery.

I also hope to have someone with me for support during the birth, whether it's a friend or someone from the clinic, just to have that emotional backing. I think it would help ease my anxiety a lot to have someone there who understands what I’m going through. 

However, I’m a bit worried about the actual hospital experience, especially since I’ve heard that it can be pretty busy and chaotic. I just want to make sure I feel heard and taken care of during that time. I think discussing this with my healthcare provider more would be beneficial, but I haven’t had the chance to go into detail yet. 

Overall, I want to ensure that I’m making informed choices for myself and the baby, but it’s hard to gather all the information I need to feel confident about my plan. I really wish there were more resources available to help guide me through this process. 

Interviewer: It sounds like you have some thoughtful preferences for your birth plan, but I understand how challenging it can be to navigate the information and support needed for such an important event. Have you discussed your birth plan preferences with your healthcare provider, or is there anything specific you would like to address with them regarding your delivery?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What sources of information have you used to learn about pregnancy and childbirth?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Persona: I've mostly relied on online resources to learn about pregnancy and childbirth. I’ve looked up articles, videos, and forums that discuss different aspects of pregnancy, what to expect during labor, and tips for taking care of myself and the baby. Websites like What to Expect and BabyCenter have been helpful for understanding developmental milestones and general advice.

I also follow some social media accounts dedicated to maternal health, which provide useful information and community support. That being said, I sometimes feel overwhelmed by the amount of information out there, and it can be hard to know what’s accurate or what applies to my situation.

I’ve thought about checking out some books on pregnancy and childbirth, but I haven’t had the time or resources to get them yet. I really wish I could have more personalized guidance, especially since I’m navigating this without much support. I think discussing reliable sources with my healthcare provider would really help, but I haven’t had that opportunity yet.

Interviewer: It sounds like you're making an effort to educate yourself, but I can see how the vast amount of information can be overwhelming. Have you found any particular topics or areas where you feel you need more clarity or guidance?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How are you managing the financial aspects of pregnancy and preparing for a baby?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Persona: Managing the financial aspects of my pregnancy has been really tough. Since I come from a low-income background and don’t have insurance, every cost feels like a huge burden. I’ve been trying to budget carefully, but unexpected expenses pop up all the time, which makes it hard to plan.

I’m relying heavily on the community clinic for my prenatal care, which helps a lot since they offer services at low or no cost. However, I know there will be more expenses coming up, like hospital fees and baby supplies, and that stresses me out. I’ve been looking into local resources that might offer assistance for new parents, but I haven’t found much yet.

I also work part-time when I can, but with my school schedule, it’s challenging to find enough hours, and I worry about how I’ll manage once the baby arrives. I’ve thought about applying for government assistance programs, but I’m not sure where to start or if I’ll qualify. 

Overall, I’m trying to stay hopeful and figure things out as they come, but the financial pressure is always on my mind. I wish I had more guidance on what resources are available for young, pregnant women in my situation. It would make a big difference to have support in navigating all of this. 

Interviewer: It’s understandable to feel overwhelmed by the financial pressures, especially with so many uncertainties ahead. Have you had the chance to discuss any financial assistance options or resources with your healthcare provider or anyone at the clinic?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How has your pregnancy affected your work or employment situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Persona: My pregnancy has definitely impacted my work and employment situation. Since I’m a college student, I already have a pretty packed schedule, and balancing school with work has been a challenge. I try to work part-time whenever I can, but my hours have had to be reduced because of my pregnancy and the fatigue that comes with it. 

I’ve found it harder to keep up with my job, especially on days when I’m feeling particularly stressed or tired. There have been times I’ve had to call in sick or cancel shifts, which makes me anxious about job security, especially since I rely on that income. 

I’ve also been thinking about how I’ll manage once the baby arrives. I worry about being able to return to work and how I’ll balance everything with a newborn. I’m considering looking for jobs with more flexible hours or even ones that allow me to work from home if possible, but I haven’t started that process yet. 

Overall, the combination of my pregnancy and school has made it difficult to find a good balance, and I feel a lot of pressure to keep everything together financially while also taking care of my health and the baby. I wish I had more resources or support to help navigate this transition, especially as I think about my future employment options. 

Interviewer: It sounds like you're facing quite a few challenges in balancing work, school, and your pregnancy. Have you thought about discussing your situation with your employer or exploring any potential support programs that might help you during this time?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about the postpartum period? What plans do you have for after the baby arrives?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Persona: Yes, I've definitely thought about the postpartum period, and it’s something that weighs heavily on my mind. I know it’s going to be a huge adjustment, and I’m trying to prepare as much as I can, but there are still so many unknowns.

I’m concerned about how my body will recover after birth and what kind of support I’ll need during that time. I want to make sure I’m taking care of my physical and mental health, especially since I’ve been dealing with a lot of stress throughout my pregnancy. I’ve heard that postpartum depression can be a real issue, and I want to be aware of that so I can reach out for help if I need it.

In terms of plans, I’m hoping to have some time off from school after the baby is born, but I’m not sure how long I can take. I want to spend time bonding with the baby and adjusting to my new role as a mom, but I also worry about falling behind in my studies and work. 

I think it would really help to have a support system in place during that time, whether it’s friends, family, or community resources. I’ve been looking into local parenting groups that might offer support, but again, I haven’t found much yet. I just want to feel prepared and know that I have the resources I need to help me navigate those early days with the baby.

Overall, I’m trying to stay hopeful, but I wish I had more concrete plans or guidance for the postpartum period. It feels like another big unknown, and I want to make sure I’m ready for whatever comes my way. 

Interviewer: It's completely understandable to have those concerns about the postpartum period, especially with everything else you are managing. Have you had any discussions with your healthcare provider about postpartum care and resources that might be available to you?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Thank you for your time and for sharing your experiences with me. This concludes our interview.
